import { Meta } from '@storybook/addon-docs/blocks';

import {
  AboutHeader,
  addParentPath,
  LinkTo,
  TableOfContents,
} from '~styleguide/blocks';

import { parameters as formParameters } from './Form/Form.mdx';
import { parameters as formGroupParameters } from './FormGroup/FormGroup.mdx';
import { parameters as formGroupDescriptionParameters } from './FormGroupDescription/FormGroupDescription.mdx';
import { parameters as formGroupLabelParameters } from './FormGroupLabel/FormGroupLabel.mdx';
import { parameters as formRequiredTextParameters } from './FormRequiredText/FormRequiredText.mdx';

export const parameters = {
  id: 'Atoms/FormElements',
  title: 'FormElements',
  subtitle:
    'Ancillary descriptions for input atoms tied 1:1 with values to be submitted in a form.',
};

<Meta title="Atoms/FormElements/About" />

<AboutHeader {...parameters} />

You should generally never use these directly as a Gamut consumer. While our `Form` atoms compose the structure of these forms, we strongly recommend only creating forms with using `GridForm` or `ConnectedForm`. You should only use the form element atoms as individual elements if your interface doesn’t need to support the technical functions of a form.

Both of our Form organisms provide the following benefits:

1. **Accessibility**: All our forms handle accessibility styling and behaviors, passing tests out-of-the-box.
2. **Functionality**: Validation and submission logic is handled by the [react-hook-form](https://react-hook-form.com) library

We recommend <LinkTo id='Organisms/GridForm'>GridForm</LinkTo> if you have a form that sticks to a 12x12 visual grid with consistent vertical rhythm and grid spacing.

For everything else, we recommend <LinkTo id='Organisms/ConnectedForm'>ConnectedForm</LinkTo>.

<TableOfContents
  links={addParentPath(parameters.id, [
    formParameters,
    formGroupParameters,
    formGroupDescriptionParameters,
    formGroupLabelParameters,
    formRequiredTextParameters,
  ])}
/>

